Solution:
We need to choose 3 boys from 6, and 3 girls from 8.  The number of ways to do this is $\binom{6}{3}\binom{8}{3}$.  Using the formula $\binom{n}{k}=\frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}$, we have \begin{align*}
\binom{6}{3}\binom{8}{3}&=\frac{6!}{3!3!}\cdot\frac{8!}{3!5!}\\
&=\frac{6\cdot5\cdot4}{3\cdot2\cdot1}\cdot\frac{8\cdot7\cdot6}{3\cdot2\cdot1}\\
&=\boxed{1120}.
\end{align*}

