Let $p$, $n$, $d$, and $q$ represent the number of pennies, nickels, dimes, and quarters, respectively.  Then we have the equations \begin{align*}
1.55p+1.95n+1.35d+1.75q&=14\\
p+n+d+q&=\text{???}
\end{align*}We want to find the value of $p+n+d+q$.  Expressing $q$ in terms of $p$, $n$, and $d$, we have  \begin{align*}
q&=\frac{14-(1.55p+1.95n+1.35d)}{1.75}\\
&=\frac{40-31p-39n-27d}{14}\\
\end{align*}Substituting into the second equation, we get $$p+n+d+\frac{40-31p-39n-27d}{14}=\frac{40-17p-39n-13d}{14}.$$Since the number of coins must be an integer, we need to find the number of coins that will make the height slightly less than 14 mm and the number of coins that will make the height slightly more than 14 mm.  We see that if we use 9 quarters, 3 dimes, 1 nickel, and 4 pennies, then the stack will be slightly less than 14 mm.  If we use 9 quarters, 3 dimes, 2 nickels, and 3 pennies, then the stack will be slightly more than 14 mm.  Therefore, the number of coins in the stack is $9+3+1+4=\boxed{17}$ or $9+3+2+3=\boxed{17}$.
